[1] Birds - Louisiana (NW)
Date: Fri 30 Apr 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: Herald Tribune.com, Fri 30 Apr 2004 [edited]
<http://www.heraldtribune.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20040430/APN/404300566>


Louisiana: wild birds in 3 parishes test positive for West Nile virus
-----------------------------------------------
3 dead birds in Caddo Parish have tested positive for the mosquito-borne
West Nile virus, which is also transmitted by infected mosquitoes to
humans. The Office of Public Health (OPH) in Shreveport also reported on
Thu 29 Apr 2004 that 2 birds in Sabine Parish, and one in Webster Parish,
have tested positive. The birds include sparrows, blue jays and cardinals.
"I think the big message we have is that mosquito season is here. Everyone
needs to be on the alert and take precautions," said Jerre Perry,
administrator for OPH's Region 7, a 9-parish area in Northwest Louisiana.

Tracking infected dead birds generally predicts where the virus will show
up in humans. In 2003, the state recorded 121 human cases and 7 deaths.
Caddo and Bossier parishes together had a total of 51 human cases. These
parishes also had reported the highest number of birds testing positive for
West Nile virus, according to the state Department of Health and Hospitals.

Dan Saxon, chief biologist with Caddo Parish mosquito control, said on Thu
29 Apr that parish-wide spraying will begin on Mon night [3 May 2004], with
8 trucks in action. Until now, the parish has been doing complaint spraying
according to citizen calls, Saxon said. While the mosquito trap that Saxon
regularly checks is showing low numbers, "we're finding mosquitoes
everywhere we go to look," he said, adding that most of the mosquitoes now
are the kind that can fly 20 miles.

