[2] Sentinel chickens deployed - Utah
Date: Sun 9 May 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: The Salt Lake Tribune, Sat 8 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.sltrib.com/2004/May/05082004/utah/164581.asp>


Utah: deployment of sentinel chickens
-----------------------------------------------
For 380 young chickens, once destined for a life in the hen house, Fri [7
May 2004] brought a higher calling. The 16-week-old poults traded in
egg-laying duties for front-line positions in the war against the
mosquito-borne West Nile virus. Mosquito control officials, gathered at the
Utah County Department of Public Works campus, sent the sentinel chickens
packing to dozens of destinations across Utah. Each chicken will be dropped
into a mosquito-infested area to serve as an early-warning system for
humans. If a West Nile mosquito feeds on one of the hens, the bird will
develop certain antibodies, said Lewis Marrott, head of the Utah County
Division of Mosquito Abatement.

Once embedded in their new homes -- 5 to 10 chickens per location -- the
feathered guardians will receive weekly blood tests. The blood samples will
be sent to a state veterinary lab in Nephi. Sentinel chickens -- which are
also found in many other states -- are just one part of Utah's virus
detection program.

Even before West Nile virus came to the United States in 1999, the state
had been using chickens to find mosquito-borne diseases. State officials
also will watch horses, wild birds, mosquitoes, and humans to track the
disease's progress across Utah. "If we're anything like Colorado was last
year, we could have 1500 cases of West Nile disease and 40 deaths," said
Joseph Miner, director of the Utah County Department of Health. In 2003,
Colorado endured 2947 human cases and 61 deaths, up from 14 cases in 2002.
Colorado seems to follow a recent national trend, in which the number of
human cases soars during 2nd year the virus is present. In 2003, Utah had a
single human case, though the virus was found in mosquitoes or animals in 9
counties.

West Nile virus does not kill or sicken the chickens, which makes them
ideal detection systems, said Ken Minson, head of the South Salt Lake
Valley Mosquito Abatement District.

