[4] Human (suspected) & equine - Colorado
Date: Wed 12 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Greeley Tribune, Wed 12 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.greeleytrib.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20040512/NEWS/1051200
35&rs=2>


Colorado: 1st suspected human case of 2004
-----------------------------------------------
Weld County could once again have the 1st human case of West Nile virus
infection in Colorado. The news took Weld health officials by surprise,
even as they are gearing up for another summer full of cases. Mark Wallace,
director of the Weld County Department of Health and Environment, said many
thought the 1st human case wouldn't come for a few weeks.

The Colorado Department of Agriculture, on Mon 10 May 2004, reported the
1st equine West Nile case for the state.

Blood from a Weld County resident tested positive for West Nile virus
infection, Wallace said, although it still needs to be confirmed by the
state health department and the Center for Disease Control. Health
officials said those tests probably won't be available for a week. The
name, age or residence of the Weld County victim was not available. The
person was not hospitalized but had symptoms consistent with West Nile,
leading to the reason for the test, Wallace said.

In 2003, 402 residents were diagnosed with West Nile virus infection, and
of those, 5 died, including the 1st death in the state. Weld County has had
the 1st human cases in the state in the past 2 years.

Usually dead birds are the 1st sign of the disease, followed by equine
cases, and, finally, humans. But in 2004, Wallace said dead birds had been
reported, but he wasn't aware of a bird testing positive for the virus in
2004 by the Weld County health department. Colorado Mosquito Control is
finding mosquitoes in its traps in Weld County, although the numbers are
low. The company, which is contracting with Weld for a USD 450 000 mosquito
control program, started putting larvacide in areas with standing water a
week or two ago. The company won't start spraying until the mosquito
numbers are much higher. Residents who are concerned about high numbers of
mosquitoes in their neighborhoods can call the company for spraying.
Colorado Mosquito Control has more than 800 traps in the Greeley area, and,
for now, at least few of the species of mosquitoes that carry West Nile
have been discovered, said Tony Stilwell, operations manager for Colorado
Mosquito control. Stilwell said some people are mistaking midge flies, and
so-called floodwater mosquitoes, for _Culex tarsalis_ mosquitoes.
Floodwater mosquitoes do not transmit West Nile virus.

[Byline: Dan England]

